    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>KOREA TO MERGE TROUBLED BANKS</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Samuel Len</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Len, Samuel</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>South Korean government will merge ailing banks that have been kept afloat with injections of taxpayers' money to speed reforms within troubled financial industry (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To speed up reforms within its troubled financial industry, the South Korean government plans to merge ailing banks that have been kept afloat with injections of taxpayers' money, the Financial Supervisory Commission said. ''Beginning in July, we will guide banks to restructure themselves, based on whether or not they have received public funds,'' said Jin Dong Soo, an official at the commission.</p>
        <p>Samuel Len (NYT)</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To speed up reforms within its troubled financial industry, the South Korean government plans to merge ailing banks that have been kept afloat with injections of taxpayers' money, the Financial Supervisory Commission said. ''Beginning in July, we will guide banks to restructure themselves, based on whether or not they have received public funds,'' said Jin Dong Soo, an official at the commission.</p>
        <p>Samuel Len (NYT)</p>
